imagining israel palestine peace why international law matters stanford law school stanford law school search utility navigation test directory news center library events publications contact & maps information for prospective students alumni employers current students faculty & staff calendar imagining israel palestine peace why international law matters go back details february 6 2012 from 7 00 pm 9 00 pm room 290 stanford law school since 1991 countless summits have been held and proclamations issued declaring a commitment to end the israeli palestinian conflict these efforts have all failed and the situation on the ground from increasing violence to the rapid expansion of the occupation infrastructure has only worsened why can an increased emphasis on international law as the basis for negotiation save the crumbling peace process what's next for israel palestine and the middle east richard falk the former albert g milbank emeritus professor of international law and practice at princeton university has served since 2008 as the united nations special rapporteur for the situation of human rights in the palestinian territories since 1967 he has authored over twenty books on international law and politics focusing on core issues at the intersection of law human rights and war was a member of the independent international commission on kosovo 1999 2001 and is currently a visiting distinguished professor at the university of california at santa barbara the talk is co sponsored by students for palestinian equal rights stanford international human rights & conflict resolution clinic the advanced degree students association & the stanford association for law in the middle east contact omar shakir oshakir stanford edu 4083904802 related international law society ils fair 44 f 2012 stanford university system requirements help virtual tour
